      {
        "id": "https://economic-research.bnpparibas.com/Media-Library/en-US/India-Robust-growth-AI-poses-challenges-employment-3/6/2026,c44718",
        "title": "India: Robust growth, but AI poses challenges for employment",
        "link": "https://economic-research.bnpparibas.com/Media-Library/en-US/India-Robust-growth-AI-poses-challenges-employment-3/6/2026,c44718",
        "content": "India’s economic growth is projected to be +7.6% for FY 2025/26, ranking among the highest in Asia. Monetary easing and VAT cuts have bolstered domestic demand. The medium-term outlook remains favourable. The  reduction in US tariffs and the gradual rollout of new free trade agreements (FTAs)—including with the US, EU, UK and EFTA—should bolster exports. After decades of protectionism, India is opening up its economy to attract FDI, develop industry, and create high-quality jobs. The government acknowledges the risks that AI poses to employment in the IT services sector.",
        "fullContent": "India’s economic growth is projected to be +7.6% for FY 2025/26, ranking among the highest in Asia. Monetary easing and VAT cuts have bolstered domestic demand. The medium-term outlook remains favourable. The  reduction in US tariffs and the gradual rollout of new free trade agreements (FTAs)—including with the US, EU, UK and EFTA—should bolster exports. After decades of protectionism, India is opening up its economy to attract FDI, develop industry, and create high-quality jobs. The government acknowledges the risks that AI poses to employment in the IT services sector.",
